00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:54.680
People find a way to do it.

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:57.650
And I always come back to
Paul Kalanithi who wrote

00:33:57.650 --> 00:33:58.950
"When Breath Becomes Air"

00:33:58.950 --> 00:34:02.480
when he had stage IV lung
cancer and was dying.

00:34:02.480 --> 00:34:06.880
Like if he can do that,
you all can write a book.

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:08.180
That's it.

00:34:08.180 --> 00:34:09.480
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much.

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:10.780
&gt;&gt; You're welcome.

00:34:10.780 --> 00:34:12.080
Yes. Hello.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:13.590
&gt;&gt; One of the things that
impressed me the most

00:34:13.590 --> 00:34:19.470 position:56%
about your story was even though you
developed an early fear of failure,

00:34:19.470 --> 00:34:20.900
you didn't take the easy way out.

00:34:20.900 --> 00:34:22.680
And just not try.

00:34:22.680 --> 00:34:25.630
But you kept on being
persistent in spite of that.

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:28.270
You didn't let the fear of
failure stop you from trying.

00:34:28.270 --> 00:34:29.590
How is it that you developed that?

00:34:29.590 --> 00:34:35.060
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: I have to give
a lot of credit to my parents.

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:36.720
I had a tiger dad.

00:34:36.720 --> 00:34:42.700
He was very much like, you will
be awesome or you will be nothing.

00:34:42.700 --> 00:34:45.560
I think that my parents
were a huge part of it.

00:34:45.560 --> 00:34:48.560
They really, really helped me
understand that if I wanted

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:51.710
to be anybody, I could not give up.

00:34:51.710 --> 00:34:55.440
And then I do think that part of it
was really a natural stubbornness.

00:34:55.440 --> 00:34:57.200
I'm the youngest of three kids.

00:34:57.200 --> 00:35:01.940 position:56%
You know you have two older brothers
who were typical older brothers.

00:35:01.940 --> 00:35:04.760
And who definitely didn't let
me get away with anything.

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:07.280
And I think that also
had a big part of it.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:09.710
And also, there is this
thing called self-talk.

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:11.480
Apparently Navy Seals do it.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:12.780
Just saying.

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:15.600
But what you basically do
is you keep telling yourself

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:17.070
that you can do something.

00:35:17.070 --> 00:35:18.370
Whatever it is.

00:35:18.370 --> 00:35:21.450
And you keep reminding yourself
of that in any way you can.

00:35:21.450 --> 00:35:22.980
And I found that really helpful.

00:35:22.980 --> 00:35:27.310
And we have about two minutes,
so maybe two more questions.

00:35:27.310 --> 00:35:29.430
Let's go to this side.

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:34.440
&gt;&gt; Hi. I wanted to know if it was
hard to keep a story line going

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:40.190
with different books and not
let it be repetitive, I guess?

00:35:40.190 --> 00:35:41.490
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: It can be.

00:35:41.490 --> 00:35:45.430 position:56%
Yes. But generally, I have this sort
of story of the characters plotted

00:35:45.430 --> 00:35:47.990
out in my head, like
all the way until death.

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:53.740 position:56%
And so, it's not as hard as I think
it could have been had I not planned

00:35:53.740 --> 00:35:55.920
out the books ahead of time.

00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:59.760
That doesn't make them
easier to write by the way.

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:01.150
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:02.450
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: Hello.

00:36:02.450 --> 00:36:04.450
&gt;&gt; Would you ever consider
writing a superhero novel?

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:08.440
I know they're a big trend in
[inaudible] literature lately?

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:09.740
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: I would.

00:36:09.740 --> 00:36:11.040
Yes. I would.

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:12.340
&gt;&gt; What superhero would
you want to .

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:13.640
. .

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:14.940
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: Ms. Marble.

00:36:14.940 --> 00:36:16.760
[Laughs] I haven't
thought about this at all.

00:36:16.760 --> 00:36:20.370
Not once. Yes.

00:36:20.370 --> 00:36:23.660
&gt;&gt; Hi. First, I just want to say
that I really love your new covers

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:26.820
because it's one of the first
times that I've seen myself

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.770
on a cover as a brown girl.

00:36:28.770 --> 00:36:30.070
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: Yes.

00:36:30.070 --> 00:36:31.370
Thank you.

00:36:31.370 --> 00:36:34.590
I'm so glad you like them.

00:36:34.590 --> 00:36:36.590
&gt;&gt; I was wondering
how do you work to get

00:36:36.590 --> 00:36:38.950
over writer's block
when you have it?

00:36:38.950 --> 00:36:40.250
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: Oh,
I love this question.

00:36:40.250 --> 00:36:41.680
Because I didn't used
to have an answer.

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:43.290
And then one of my
friends provided an answer.

00:36:43.290 --> 00:36:45.670
And I have since stole it from her.

00:36:45.670 --> 00:36:47.950
So, Alison Goodman who
wrote the "Eon" books

00:36:47.950 --> 00:36:50.270
and the "Dark Days Club" books says

00:36:50.270 --> 00:36:52.090
that she doesn't believe
in writer's block.

00:36:52.090 --> 00:36:54.330
She believes in writer's pause.

00:36:54.330 --> 00:36:58.050
And that's what I've been sort
of thinking about recently.

00:36:58.050 --> 00:36:59.450
It's not that I'm blocked.

00:36:59.450 --> 00:37:03.550
It's that something has gone
wrong in the past whatever,

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:05.070
however many pages I've written.

00:37:05.070 --> 00:37:07.570
That has made me not
know what to do next.

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:10.140
So, what I do is I go
back to the last place

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:11.750
that the story has worked.

00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:13.050
And I start from there.

00:37:13.050 --> 00:37:14.350
And I try to start looking at it.

00:37:14.350 --> 00:37:15.980
Okay, this is where
the story was flowing.

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:18.930
What happened afterward
that isn't working.

00:37:18.930 --> 00:37:23.480
Generally, it's something like my
characters' motivations are right.

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:24.980
Or the conflict doesn't quite fit.

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:26.960
There is something off.

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:29.880
So, if you're struggling
with writer's pause,

00:37:29.880 --> 00:37:33.260
go back to the last place that
felt good and start from there.

00:37:33.260 --> 00:37:34.800
And start sort of going through.

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:39.000
And one more question
and then we'll be done.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.160
&gt;&gt; thank you for coming
and joining us today.

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:45.310
And my question is where do
you get your inspiration from?

00:37:45.310 --> 00:37:48.470
&gt;&gt; Sabaa Tahir: So, I get my
inspiration almost primarily

00:37:48.470 --> 00:37:50.690
from news stories that I read.

00:37:50.690 --> 00:37:55.170
And more recently reading about
the refugee crisis in Europe

00:37:55.170 --> 00:37:57.080
and the Middle East has
been a huge inspiration

00:37:57.080 --> 00:37:58.470
for the stuff I've written.

00:37:58.470 --> 00:38:01.060
It has found its way into
Torch, in particular,

00:38:01.060 --> 00:38:03.610
and it will be finding
its way into Reaper.

00:38:03.610 --> 00:38:06.760
So, yes. that's why I said
read the Washington Post.

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:08.060
And with that.

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:09.860
Thank you, guys very
much for coming.

